### 9. Volkite Weapons

**Signature Rule:** ***Deflagrate*** (each model slain generates one additional automatic hit at same S/AP)

**Identity:** Dark Age of Technology thermic ray weapons. The beam causes a chain reaction in organic matter — kills propagate through nearby targets. Rare, revered, and devastating against massed infantry.

| Weapon | Range | S | AP | Type | Notes |
| :---- | :---: | :---: | :---: | :---- | :---- |
| Volkite Serpenta | 10" | 5 | 5 | Pistol 2, Deflagrate | Officer sidearm. |
| Volkite Charger | 15" | 5 | 5 | Assault 2, Deflagrate | Standard infantry volkite. |
| Volkite Caliver | 30" | 6 | 5 | Heavy 2, Deflagrate | Heavy infantry variant. |
| Volkite Culverin | 45" | 6 | 5 | Heavy 6, Deflagrate | Support weapon. |

**Baseline:** S5 AP5, scaling to S6 at the heavy tier. Range scales dramatically (10" → 45"). AP stays at 5 — volkite weapons rely on Deflagrate chain reactions rather than armor penetration.

**Known Inconsistency:** The Space Marines codex currently lists volkite weapons with ***Disintegrating Beam*** instead of ***Deflagrate***. This must be corrected during the SM weapons pass.

**Factions:** Imperium (Heresy-era relics, primarily Space Marines and Mechanicus).

---

### 10. Graviton Weapons

**Signature Rule:** ***Graviton*** + ***Concussive***. Heavy variants additionally gain ***Pinning***.

**Identity:** Localized gravity manipulation. Heavier armor = more damage (wound roll equals target's armor save). The crushing gravitational force stuns targets (Concussive) and at high intensity pins them flat (Pinning).

| Weapon | Range | Type | Notes |
| :---- | :---: | :---- | :---- |
| Grav Pistol | 12" | Pistol | Graviton, Concussive. |
| Grav-gun | 18" | Rapid Fire | Graviton, Concussive. |
| Grav Cannon + Grav-amp | 24" | Heavy | Graviton, Concussive, **Pinning**. Grav-amp provides re-rolls. |

**Note:** Graviton weapons have no standard S value — the Graviton USR replaces the normal wound roll. Against vehicles: D6, immobilized on a 6.

**Factions:** Imperium (primarily Space Marines), Leagues of Votann.

---

### 11. Autocannons

**Signature Rule:** ***Rending***

**Identity:** High-velocity, large-calibre solid-shot weapons. The sheer kinetic energy of the rounds occasionally finds weak points in armor, punching well above the weapon's nominal penetration. Rending (wound roll of 6 = auto-wound at AP2; pen roll of 6 = +D3) gives autocannons a meaningful ceiling against heavy targets without inflating their base stats.

| Weapon | Range | S | AP | Type | Notes |
| :---- | :---: | :---: | :---: | :---- | :---- |
| Autocannon | 48" | 7 | 4 | Heavy 2, Rending | Standard profile. |
| Twin-linked Autocannon | 48" | 7 | 4 | Heavy 2, Twin-Linked, Rending | — |
| Twin-linked Icarus Autocannons | 48" | 7 | 4 | Heavy 2, Twin-Linked, Skyfire, Interceptor, Rending | Anti-air variant. |

**Baseline:** 48" S7 AP4 Heavy 2. Extremely consistent across all appearances.

**Known Inconsistency:** No existing OmniHammer autocannon profiles currently carry Rending. This is a new convention — Rending must be added to all autocannon profiles as they are written or updated.

**Factions:** Imperium (all), Chaos.

---

### 12. Rad Weapons

**Signature Rule:** ***Rad-Phage*** + ***Poison (2+)*** + ***Ignores Cover***

**Identity:** Cross-spectrum radiation projectors. Radiation doesn't care about your cover (Ignores Cover), bypasses conventional toughness (Poison 2+), and causes lasting cellular degradation (Rad-Phage permanently reduces Toughness by 1). Dark Age of Technology horror weapons.

| Weapon | Range | S | AP | Type | Notes |
| :---- | :---: | :---: | :---: | :---- | :---- |
| Rad Cleanser (Knight) | Template | 2 | 5 | Assault 1, Rad-Phage, Poison (2+), Ignores Cover | Built into Hekaton Siege Claw. |
| Irrad-Cleanser (SM) | 24" | — | 5 | Heavy 1, Blast, Poison (2+), Ignores Cover | **Needs Rad-Phage added.** |

**Baseline:** Low or no S (relies on Poison for wounding), AP5, all three signature rules present. Useless against vehicles (Poison has no effect on vehicles per core rules) — rad weapons are pure anti-infantry.

**Known Inconsistency:** The Irrad-Cleanser in the Space Marines codex is missing ***Rad-Phage***. This must be added.

**Factions:** Imperium (Mechanicus, Space Marines Saturnine Terminators, Knights).

---

### 13. Phosphor Weapons

**Signature Rule:** ***Luminagen*** (***Blind*** + target's cover saves reduced by 1 until end of turn; does not stack with itself)

**Identity:** Incendiary marking rounds that burn with intense white light. Strips concealment and blinds targets. A tactical illumination/suppression tool, not a killing weapon.

| Weapon | Range | S | AP | Type | Notes |
| :---- | :---: | :---: | :---: | :---- | :---- |
| Phosphor Blaster | 24" | 5 | 4 | Heavy 2, Luminagen | Currently only defined member. |

**Baseline:** S5 AP4 expected. More members (Phosphor Serpenta, Heavy Phosphor Blaster) will be defined when the Mechanicus codex is written.

**Distinct from Phosphex.** Phosphor is a marking round. Phosphex is a war crime. See Family 14.

**Factions:** Imperium (Mechanicus, Knights).

---

### 14. Phosphex Weapons

**Signature Rule:** ***Phosphex*** USR + ***Ignores Cover*** on initial hit

**Identity:** A Dark Age of Technology chemical horror weapon. Self-guided, crawling fire that seeks organic matter, burns through anything, and cannot be extinguished. Banned after the Heresy. Leaves permanent dead zones.

**Phosphex USR (NEW):**

> ***Phosphex:*** A weapon with this special rule uses a blast marker. After resolving the initial attack, leave the blast marker in place for the remainder of the game. The marker is dangerous terrain that provides no cover.
>
> Any model that begins its turn under the marker, or moves through the marker during the Movement or Assault phases, suffers a **S5 AP3** hit with ***Ignores Cover***. A model may only suffer hits from each individual Phosphex marker once per turn. A model may suffer hits from multiple different Phosphex markers in the same turn.
>
> Against vehicles, resolve hits against the armor facing closest to the center of the marker.

**Baseline:** No profiles written yet. Convention ready for Heresy-era weapons (Phosphex Bomb Clusters, Phosphex Dischargers) when relevant codexes are written.

**Distinct from Phosphor.** See Family 13.

**Factions:** Heresy-era Imperium, Death Guard, Mechanicum remnants.

---

### 15. Missile Weapons

**Signature Rule:** None (warhead-defined, not a technology family)

**Identity:** Missiles are a delivery system, not a technology. Their rules are defined by the warhead they carry, not by being a missile. Frag missiles are blast weapons, Krak missiles are anti-armor, Flakk missiles are anti-air.

**Common warhead types:**
- **Frag:** S4 AP6, Blast — anti-infantry fragmentation.
- **Krak:** S8 AP3 — anti-armor solid shot.
- **Flakk:** S7 AP4, Skyfire — anti-aircraft.
- **Seeker (Tau):** S8 AP3, One Use — guided munition.

**Note:** Ork Rokkits typically carry ***Backblast***. This is an Ork engineering convention, not a missile family rule.

**Factions:** Universal.

---

### 16. Conversion Beamer Weapons

**Signature Rule:** Range-dependent profiles that increase in power with distance

**Identity:** Weapons that convert ambient matter into energy, becoming more powerful the further the beam travels. Defined by their variable profile mechanic — weaker up close, devastating at range.

| Range Bracket | Typical S | Typical AP | Notes |
| :---- | :---: | :---: | :---- |
| Close (0–18") | 6 | — | Minimal effect. |
| Medium (18–42") | 8 | 4 | Blast added. |
| Long (42–72") | 10 | 1 | Large Blast, maximum power. |

**Members:** Conversion Beamer, Conversion Beam Obliterator (Knight Defender). Votann HEKAS beam weapons may belong to this family (TBD).

**Factions:** Imperium (Mechanicus, Knights), possibly Leagues of Votann.

